snippet.textDisplay:
Here's the translation to the song

O Shyam (Krishna), the dark one,
O playful flute player, O playful one,
Your cows graze in the fields,
Who has tended to them, O Hari (Krishna)?Under the shade of the kadam tree,
Kanai (Krishna) plays his flute.
O Ram, under the kadam tree,
Kanai plays his flute.On the banks of the Yamuna,
Shyam, the dark one,
Krishna plays his flute,
O playful flute player.With flowing hair, O Hari,
Under the shade of the kadam tree,
Kanai plays his flute.O Shyam, where will you flee today?
O Shyam, where will you run?
To the banks of the Yamuna,
Or under the kadam tree?
They will catch you and tie you up.
O Shyam, where will you flee today?In the fields of Vrindavan, O Kanu (Krishna),
O Shyam, the dark one,
Your cows graze, O Lord,
O Shyam, the dark one.The sound of your flute
Captivates the hearts of the gopis (cowherd girls).
O Shyam, where will you flee today?
To the banks of the Yamuna,
Or under the kadam tree?
They will catch you and tie you up.
O Shyam, where will you flee today?

Cultural Context: The song is a traditional Assamese folk composition that celebrates Lord Krishna, often referred to as Shyam, Kanai, or Kanu. The lyrics depict Krishna's playful nature, his flute-playing, and his life as a cowherd in Vrindavan. The kadam tree and Yamuna river are iconic settings in Krishna's lore.
